How to Easily Fix Low Audio Volume after Installing Custom ROMs
(Compatible with CyanogenMod)

.1   The first thing to do will be to download ES File Explorer app on
your device from Google Play – open Google Play, search for the app
and install it on your Android device.

.2   Next, you have to enable root explorer in the same app, as this
option comes disabled by default.

.3   So, runt the app and then tap on icon at top left to open its menu;
from there choose Tools and then turn on the Root Explorer option.

.4   Write capabilities must also be ensured on ES File Explorer. In
order to achieve that, you have to tap once on the “Root Explorer”
text in order to launch general options. Now tap on Mount R/W, and then
select /system as R/W. Save your changes in the end.

.5   Up next, from the ES File Explorer app, navigate towards
“/device/etc/sound” and find the file dubbed as “to3g”.

.6   Tap on that file and select “open as text”.

.7   What you need to do next is to change the default sound volume
values as in the following examples:
.. <ctl name="Speaker Volume" val="57"/> -> "60" or "63"
.. <ctl name="Output Volume" val="xx"/> -> "62"
.. optional
... <ctl name="AIF1 Boost Volume" val="2"/>
... <ctl name="AIF2 Boost Volume" val="2"/>

.8 That’s it; save the file when you’re done.

